class Solution {
    public int lengthOfLongestSubstring(String s) {
        HashSet<Character> temp = new HashSet<Character>();
        int l=0, r=0, max=0;
        for(int i=0; i<s.length();i++){
            while(r<s.length() && !temp.contains(s.charAt(r))){
                temp.add(s.charAt(r));
                max=Math.max(max,r-l+1);
                r++;
            }
            temp.remove(s.charAt(l));
            l++;
        }
        return max;
    }
}

/*
Note:

1.	 “HashSet”: The difference between HashSet and HashMap:
             HASHSET	                                                                                          HASHMAP
HashSet only maintains value.   e.g. {“Hello”, “Hi”, “Bye”, “Run”}	                     HashMap maintains the key & value.  e.g. {1->”Hello”, 2->”Hi”, 3->”Bye”, 4->”Run”}                                                       
HashSet can’t store duplicate values in HashSet.	                                     HashMap does not allow duplicate keys however it allows to have duplicate values.
HashSet permits to have a single null value.	                                         HashMap permits single null key and any number of null values.
HashSet.contains("Value");	                                                             HashMap.containsKey(“Key element”)
HashSet.add();	                                                                         HashMap.put();

2.	String “charAt(int index)” Method: d returns the character at the specified index(0,1,2…) in a string.
    String myStr = "Hello";
    char result = myStr.charAt(0);
    System.out.println(result);

3.	“Math.max(a,b)”: return the biggest value between a and b.
   max=Math.max(a,b);
*/
